isten on Spotify [ https://substack.com/redirect/345bc988-2cea-4779-b252-95=
b31151195e?r=3D9p0gt ] or=C2=A0Apple Podcasts [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/39d8b885-4e64-4e30-9bbb-c543c4ce6ad9?r=3D9p0gt ]
Today=E2=80=99s Not Boring, the whole thing, is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 =
Tegus [ https://substack.com/redirect/ae8d9e01-b7ff-4dc1-80c0-5d9f5f833e16?=
r=3D9p0gt ]
Not Boring readers can try Tegus for free [ https://substack.com/redirect/a=
e8d9e01-b7ff-4dc1-80c0-5d9f5f833e16?r=3D9p0gt ]. Sign up by clicking this b=
utton to explore expert calls on hundreds of companies like Stripe, SpaceX,=
 Meta, Anduril, Amazon, and more. =20
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=20
Happy Thursday!=20
As someone who uses Tegus whenever I begin researching a new company to wri=
te about, I=E2=80=99m really excited to bring you the first inside look at =
the company ever written.=20
It=E2=80=99s clear from talking to the team, and from looking at the number=
s, that this is a special company that is going to be around for a long tim=
e. It=E2=80=99s also the perfect company to study right now, in a market th=
at once again values free cash flow, strategic chops, and smart capital all=
ocation.=20
This essay is a Sponsored Deep Dive. As a testament to my genuine love of t=
he product, I traded an equivalent amount of the deep dive rate for free ac=
cess to Tegus for a year. You can read more about how I choose which compan=
ies to do deep dives on, and how I write them here [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/b5b8370b-8af6-4b84-99fc-b611c91c2d68?r=3D9p0gt ].
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
Tegus: The Outsiders
It feels almost disrespectful to call Tegus [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/ff6c425a-858c-41be-8c1f-b24669497f4e?r=3D9p0gt ] a unicorn. Too fluffy.=C2=
=A0
Sure, the five-year-old company has all the markings of the mythical creatu=
re:=C2=A0
$3+ billion valuation as of its Series B in November 2021 (it=E2=80=99s sin=
ce raised another round at an undisclosed valuation)=C2=A0
195% year-over-year ARR growth off of a very meaningful base
Over 2,500 customers
Nearly 700 employees
The company=E2=80=99s Series A, led by the Investment Group of Santa Barbar=
a at a $4.5 million post-money valuation, is already one of the best ventur=
e investments I=E2=80=99ve come across. IGSB=E2=80=99s $1.5 million investm=
ent is already worth around $1 billion on paper, assuming they still hold t=
hat entire position. That=E2=80=99s good for a ~350% IRR as of the company=
=E2=80=99s last announced round in November 2021.=C2=A0
If those numbers belonged to nearly any other company, you would have heard=
 about them on Twitter. There would be cover stories written, highlighting =
brother co-founders Tom and Mike Elnick.=C2=A0
Instead, this is the first time the Tegus story has really been told public=
ly. This is what you get when you search =E2=80=9CElnick=E2=80=9D in Spotif=
y podcasts:
If you=E2=80=99re a religious Invest Like the Best [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/eff3d415-e93d-4661-bc1d-4296d36493b5?r=3D9p0gt ] listener like I am=
, you=E2=80=99ve known about Tegus for a few years, but besides a few targe=
ted ads, Tom and Mike have eschewed the spotlight in favor of a maniacal fo=
cus on finding genuine product market fit (PMF) with an intentionally narro=
w set of users.=C2=A0
They=E2=80=99ve =E2=80=9Cgone slow to go fast.=E2=80=9D Which makes sense, =
because unlike the typical unicorn founders, Tom and Mike aren=E2=80=99t co=
ders, they=E2=80=99re distance runners. And their discipline, patience, and=
 pacing shine through in every aspect of the business.=C2=A0
Tegus is building the modern investment research platform for fundamental p=
rivate and public market investors, starting with a novel twist on the clas=
sic expert call model, and expanding into adjacent opportunities by listeni=
ng intently to customers.=C2=A0
Yes yes, every company says that they listen to customers, but as Tegus CFO=
 Bob Casey put it, =E2=80=9CIf the CEO=E2=80=99s calendar is indicative of =
what=E2=80=99s most valuable in an organization, Tom and Mike=E2=80=99s cal=
endars overwhelmingly point to customer obsession.=E2=80=9D Before emailing=
 me on Sunday, Casey checked Tom and Mike=E2=80=99s calendars for the week,=
 and counted 14 customer calls between Monday morning and Wednesday afterno=
on. Casey himself has 20 customer meetings lined up when he=E2=80=99s in NY=
C next week.=C2=A0=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s just one of many anecdotes that hint at Tegus=E2=80=99 uniqu=
e approach. Learn how Tegus got here, and how it thinks and behaves today, =
and you=E2=80=99ll realize that it=E2=80=99s different than the typical Sil=
icon Valley success story.=C2=A0
For one thing, the company is free cash flow positive, and has been for yea=
rs, even before it was cool. It=E2=80=99s also built for the long-term, wit=
h an eye towards doing this for decades that comes through in every decisio=
n the company makes. Tom and Mike have studied Hamilton Helmer=E2=80=99s 7 =
Powers [ https://substack.com/redirect/52dd9cdb-c278-4012-9b49-f844be43a818=
?r=3D9p0gt ] and Will Thorndike=E2=80=99s The Outsiders [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/ed95557c-798d-40fa-b700-8fa5c61cc363?r=3D9p0gt ] more than any=
one besides maybe Ben [ https://substack.com/redirect/ee7eb95b-9b90-4f2d-b7=
76-240acdd89353?r=3D9p0gt ] and David [ https://substack.com/redirect/48938=
479-67f9-46c9-81f5-54ec98593848?r=3D9p0gt ] at Acquired [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/f1951021-c92a-430b-9894-29d57c36d1ec?r=3D9p0gt ], and they=E2=
=80=99ve put the lessons to work:=C2=A0=C2=A0
7 Powers: building a business with sustainable differentiation, which lever=
aged counter positioning in the early days and enjoys scale economies today
The Outsiders: smart capital allocation, as evidenced by the facts that, in=
 just five years, the company has already done a share buyback and three ac=
quisitions, including BamSEC [ https://substack.com/redirect/ef6dbf08-a89d-=
4086-8da3-d66361f85582?r=3D9p0gt ] and Canalyst [ https://substack.com/redi=
rect/058ca76a-d6b9-4700-a409-f013735c9c4a?r=3D9p0gt ]=C2=A0
Tegus is a business that combines the pace of a startup with the maturity o=
f a more established company. It reminds me of the companies that fintwit l=
oves, the ones you haven=E2=80=99t heard a lot about that are just spitting=
 off cash, allocating capital wisely, with strong management teams at the h=
elm. With markets turning, profitability and sound strategy back in vogue, =
and real, recurring, defensible revenue at a premium, Tegus is the perfect =
company for entrepreneurs and investors alike to study.=C2=A0
So let=E2=80=99s study Tegus. Today, we=E2=80=99ll pull back the curtains t=
o cover:
The Course to Tegus
Modernizing Investment Research=C2=A0
The Tegus Business Model=C2=A0
The Outsiders: Fundraising, Buybacks, and Acquisitions
When I asked Mike what he was hoping readers get out of this piece, he told=
 me:=C2=A0
For a long time, we=E2=80=99ve been very misunderstood, and we=E2=80=99ve b=
een thrilled to be misunderstood. 10 out of 10 times we would have chosen t=
o be under the radar. But now we have 2,500 customers, and we can=E2=80=99t=
 skirt through the rest of the company=E2=80=99s life without telling our s=
tory.
=F0=9F=AB=A1 It=E2=80=99s time to tell the Tegus story.=C2=A0
The Course to Tegus
Tom and Mike Elnick grew up on Long Island with chips on their shoulders.=
=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWe were so competitive with each other,=E2=80=9D Mike told me, =E2=
=80=9Cbecause we wanted to prove our doubters wrong through our own competi=
tive process.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The result was, as the first in their family to go away to college, they en=
ded up at an Ivy, Brown University, where they ran track and cross country.=
 Mike went shorter, running the 800, and Tom went longer, to the 5k. They m=
et in the middle racing the mile, where Tom bested Mike with a PR of 4:08 t=
o his brother=E2=80=99s 4:12.=C2=A0
Whether they ran because of who they were, or whether running shaped them i=
nto who they are, the sport=E2=80=99s footprint is all over the brothers an=
d the company they=E2=80=99ve built. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s this notion o=
f =E2=80=98you gotta keep on training,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Tom explained. =E2=
=80=9CYou can have a bad race, but you still have to put in your 70 miles e=
very week.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
After school, Tom and Mike split for the first time. Tom went to work for O=
verbrook Management, a value oriented long/short hedge fund, as an Analyst.=
 Mike went to expert network startup AlphaSights as one of its earliest emp=
loyees. In those roles, they saw the inefficiencies of the investment resea=
rch process from both sides, and it bugged them.=C2=A0
Not enough to start a company =E2=80=93 they were risk-averse =E2=80=93 but=
 enough to start asking around. When they asked other investors about their=
 research process, they=E2=80=99d get agreement that the process wasn=E2=80=
=99t as smooth as it could be, followed inevitably by a: =E2=80=9CBut that=
=E2=80=99s just the way it is.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
As competitive people, hearing =E2=80=9Cbut that=E2=80=99s just the way it =
is=E2=80=9D over and over again lit a fire and pushed them, hesitantly, int=
o entrepreneurship. On September 11, 2015, Tom and Mike quit their respecti=
ve jobs and teamed up once again, not to start a company necessarily, but t=
o talk to as many investors about their process as possible to see if there=
 might be a way to change the way it just was.=C2=A0
Modernizing Investment Research
There are many different ways to invest: quant funds, macro funds, event-dr=
iven funds, high-frequency funds, all flavors of funds. Tom and Mike were f=
ocused on speaking with investors at funds doing fundamental research, thos=
e trying to understand the businesses in which they invest more deeply than=
 anyone else in order to develop a differentiated view on their value. As e=
xamples, current Tegus customers [ https://substack.com/redirect/d1e7dca2-e=
8b2-4901-a9c7-cad94a212e0d?r=3D9p0gt ] include ShawSpring Partners, Thrive =
Capital, Octahedron, Accel, Mission Holdings, Redpoint, O=E2=80=99Shaughnes=
sy Asset Management, and IGSB, all funds whose investors I respect for thei=
r insightfulness.=C2=A0
A lot of inputs inform those funds=E2=80=99 views, but generally, there are=
 three core elements that all fundamental investors focus on:=C2=A0
Qualitative Research: understanding how the business works
Previous Performance: using company filings to understand a business=E2=80=
=99 financials
Models: building models to analyze a business under various scenarios and a=
ssumptions
The existing process =E2=80=93 which uses a mix of Bloomberg, CapIQ, FactSe=
t, GLG, AlphaSights, Edgar, S&P Global, and a menagerie of other data sourc=
es =E2=80=93 works well enough to elicit =E2=80=9Cthat=E2=80=99s just the w=
ay it works=E2=80=9D responses, but it=E2=80=99s time consuming and expensi=
ve. Analysts at investment funds are among the highest-paid professionals i=
n the world, and they can spend up to two-thirds of their time finding, agg=
regating, and manipulating data. That leaves less time for analysis and cre=
ativity, the things that actually justify the big bucks.=C2=A0
So when Tom and Mike set out to figure out what was wrong with the process,=
 they focused on what they believed the biggest mismatch was between how va=
luable something was and how painful it was to access. That mismatch was th=
e largest in primary research, so they started by focusing on that gap firs=
t. They also loved that it was probably the hardest thing to tackle; no one=
 who studies this space had been able to build a disruptor.=C2=A0
Primary research, tracking people down and asking them questions, could tak=
e a week or more between finding the right person to talk to, setting up a =
call, having the call, taking notes, and synthesizing them. Plus, the incum=
bents left a lot of room for improvement, as Mike saw first hand at AlphaSi=
ghts.=C2=A0
The expert calls business has been around for a long time. As Byrne Hobart =
wrote in Tegus and the Research Stack [ https://substack.com/redirect/45449=
ce7-dee3-42e9-ab76-d004bb399387?r=3D9p0gt ]:=C2=A0
Depending on how you count, it might be one of the oldest forms of financia=
l research: if you're trying to understand what a company does, or what's h=
appening to it right now, track down someone who knows and ask them. Phil F=
isher was doing this in the 1930s and writing about it in the 1950s, and Jo=
seph de la Vega writes about looking for rumors and insights on the Dutch E=
ast India Company.=C2=A0
Today, it=E2=80=99s a lucrative business. When GLG filed to go public in Oc=
tober 2021 (it pulled the IPO in March 2022), it stated in its S-1 [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/2ac4882c-1ceb-4d88-a3ea-86dd6f46027b?r=3D9p0gt ] th=
at the company did $589 million in revenue and $34.1 million in net income =
in 2020.=C2=A0
Typically, the way it works is that an investor wants to speak with someone=
 with knowledge on a particular company or industry, say a recently former =
executive at a telecom company. They contact a firm like GLG, and GLG match=
es them with an expert. The expert charges GLG something like $300 per hour=
 for their time, GLG charges the investor something like $1,000 per hour, t=
he two parties connect, and GLG pockets a cool $700 per hour. (Numbers pure=
ly illustrative.)=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s a lot of money for an hour, but these calls often help funds=
 make decisions on investments in the tens or hundreds of millions of dolla=
rs, and expert calls are viewed as a cost of doing business. What=E2=80=99s=
 often more painful is how long it can take to get the information you want=
 =E2=80=93 often a week or more. In a business in which time is literally m=
oney, that=E2=80=99s too long.=C2=A0
The Elnicks identified primary research as the hardest problem with the gre=
atest potential gains, and they set to work figuring out how to capture tho=
se gains. They started by asking a question:=C2=A0
How do you modernize and streamline the information in peoples=E2=80=99 min=
ds on-demand?
You could survey experts and charge investors to access their responses. Or=
 maybe you could create a marketplace where experts sign up and investors m=
essage them directly. Those options could speed the process up, but they wo=
uld do so at the cost of quality and customization.=C2=A0
Instead of coming up with the answer themselves, Mike and Tom started with =
the problem that they wanted to solve, then they hit the pavement, speaking=
 with as many fundamental investors as they possibly could. They spent 18 m=
onths talking to potential customers before launching the first product.
In the earliest calls, they just wanted to understand the pain points. Peop=
le said that the process wasn=E2=80=99t perfect, but it was fine, it=E2=80=
=99s just the way it was. =E2=80=9CSure, it=E2=80=99s expensive, but we=E2=
=80=99re a hedge fund. Sure, they take a while to schedule, but these are e=
xperts, they=E2=80=99re busy.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
So they focused in on a specific idea: what if we could get customers to ge=
nerate content themselves, structure the data they generate, and then charg=
e everyone a subscription fee to access the growing treasure trove of infor=
mation?=C2=A0
With that reframing, the pushback got more specific. Some investors, believ=
ing that the information they gleaned from the questions they asked was pro=
prietary, didn=E2=80=99t feel comfortable sharing transcripts of their call=
s on the platform. Then one investor said, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d be interest=
ed in doing this, but I=E2=80=99d need a lag time.=E2=80=9D Tom and Mike as=
ked him how much lag time he=E2=80=99d need, and he said two weeks. So they=
 went back to other investors and asked if they=E2=80=99d feel comfortable =
with a two-week lag time, and many of them said yes.=C2=A0
Through this process, they tweaked and iterated the details until it formed=
 a clear outline of the product. Then, they went back and met with more cus=
tomers. The goal was to discover an =E2=80=9COver My Dead Body Product=E2=
=80=9D: a product so useful to customers that if someone threatened to take=
 it away, that=E2=80=99s how they=E2=80=99d respond.=C2=A0
Then one day, on one of those exploratory calls, they found something close=
=2E An investor told the Elnicks, =E2=80=
=9CSend us something to sign. We=E2=
=80=99ll pay you when you launch, and we=E2=80=99ll start doing calls now t=
o build up the library.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That was huge. Getting people to nod along in agreement is one thing. Getti=
ng them to loop in their ops and legal teams to hash out and sign a contrac=
t, before a single line of code had been written, was another.=C2=A0
Without building a product, Tegus had started to find product-market fit. T=
hat defined an approach the company uses to this day: Sell-Design-Build.
Over the next six weeks, 40 customers signed up.=C2=A0
So what were they signing up for? What model emerged from those hundreds of=
 conversations?=C2=A0
As one investor they spoke to told them, =E2=80=9CGo study Costco, because =
this is the Costco model.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The Tegus Business Model
The unlock was simple in retrospect: instead of charging investors a markup=
 on every expert call and keeping them siloed, like an expensive matchmakin=
g service, Tegus charges investors a subscription fee to access the platfor=
m, and then lets them book expert calls at cost.=C2=A0
On the surface, it=E2=80=99s the Costco model: sell the product at breakeve=
n, make money on the membership.=C2=A0
To read more about Tegus=E2=80=99 product, business model, and strategy, in=
cluding its recent acquisitions=E2=80=A6=20
To give you a taste for the quality of the conversations on the platform, T=
egus has opened up a free version of one of its most popular, on AWS: Acces=
s It Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/6c5bac88-cac0-4d44-9eb8-9b5c687e3=
590?r=3D9p0gt ].
If you want to try Tegus for yourself, sign up with this special Not Boring=
 link for a free trial:
