: 0; padding-left: 4px;"><strong>Previous Performance</strong><span>: using=
 company filings to understand a business&#8217; financials</span></p></li>=
<li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; col=
or: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: =
0; padding-left: 4px;"><strong>Models: </strong><span>building models to an=
alyze a business under various scenarios and assumptions</span></p></li></o=
l><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;">The existing process &#8211; which uses a mix of Bloomberg, Cap=
IQ, FactSet, GLG, AlphaSights, Edgar, S&amp;P Global, and a menagerie of ot=
her data sources &#8211; works well enough to elicit &#8220;that&#8217;s ju=
st the way it works&#8221; responses, but it&#8217;s time consuming and exp=
ensive. Analysts at investment funds are among the highest-paid professiona=
ls in the world, and they can spend up to two-thirds of their time finding,=
 aggregating, and manipulating data. That leaves less time for analysis and=
 creativity, the things that actually justify the big bucks.&#160;</p><p st=
yle=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;">So when Tom and Mike set out to figure out what was wrong with the pro=
cess, they focused on what they believed the biggest mismatch was between h=
ow valuable something was and how painful it was to access. That mismatch w=
as the largest in primary research, so they started by focusing on that gap=
 first. They also loved that it was probably the hardest thing to tackle; n=
o one who studies this space had been able to build a disruptor.&#160;</p><=
p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 =
20px 0;">Primary research, tracking people down and asking them questions, =
could take a week or more between finding the right person to talk to, sett=
ing up a call, having the call, taking notes, and synthesizing them. Plus, =
the incumbents left a lot of room for improvement, as Mike saw first hand a=
t AlphaSights.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The expert calls business has been =
around for a long time. As Byrne Hobart wrote in </span><em><a href=3D"http=
s://substack.com/redirect/45449ce7-dee3-42e9-ab76-d004bb399387?r=3D9p0gt" r=
el=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">Tegus and the=
 Research Stack</a></em><span>:&#160;</span></p><blockquote style=3D"border=
-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 20px 0;"><p style=3D"color: #404040; font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em=
>Depending on how you count, it might be one of the oldest forms of financi=
al research: if you're trying to understand what a company does, or what's =
happening to it right now, track down someone who knows and ask them. Phil =
Fisher was doing this in the 1930s and writing about it in the 1950s, and J=
oseph de la Vega writes about looking for rumors and insights on the Dutch =
East India Company.</em><span>&#160;</span></p></blockquote><p style=3D"col=
or: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span=
>Today, it&#8217;s a lucrative business. When GLG filed to go public in Oct=
ober 2021 (it pulled the IPO in March 2022), it stated in its </span><a hre=
f=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/2ac4882c-1ceb-4d88-a3ea-86dd6f46027b?r=
=3D9p0gt" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">S-=
1</a><span> that the company did $589 million in revenue and $34.1 million =
in net income in 2020.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Typically, the way it work=
s is that an investor wants to speak with someone with knowledge on a parti=
cular company or industry, say a recently former executive at a telecom com=
pany. They contact a firm like GLG, and GLG matches them with an expert. Th=
e expert charges GLG something like $300 per hour for their time, GLG charg=
es the investor something like $1,000 per hour, the two parties connect, an=
d GLG pockets a cool $700 per hour. (Numbers purely illustrative.)&#160;</p=
><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 =
0 20px 0;">That&#8217;s a lot of money for an hour, but these calls often h=
elp funds make decisions on investments in the tens or hundreds of millions=
 of dollars, and expert calls are viewed as a cost of doing business. What&=
#8217;s often more painful is how long it can take to get the information y=
ou want &#8211; often a week or more. In a business in which time is litera=
lly money, that&#8217;s too long.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The Elnicks identified=
 primary research as the hardest problem with the greatest potential gains,=
 and they set to work figuring out how to capture those gains. They started=
 by asking a question:&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px=
; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>How do you modernize and =
streamline the information in peoples&#8217; minds on-demand?</strong></p><=
p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 =
20px 0;">You could survey experts and charge investors to access their resp=
onses. Or maybe you could create a marketplace where experts sign up and in=
vestors message them directly. Those options could speed the process up, bu=
t they would do so at the cost of quality and customization.&#160;</p><p st=
yle=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;"><span>Instead of coming up with the answer themselves, Mike and Tom st=
arted with the problem that they wanted to solve, then they hit the pavemen=
t, speaking with as many fundamental investors as they possibly could. They=
 </span><strong>spent 18 months talking to potential customers before launc=
hing the first product.</strong></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In the earliest calls, they j=
ust wanted to understand the pain points. People said that the process wasn=
&#8217;t perfect, but it was fine, it&#8217;s just the way it was. &#8220;S=
ure, it&#8217;s expensive, but we&#8217;re a hedge fund. Sure, they take a =
while to schedule, but these are experts, they&#8217;re busy.&#8221;&#160;<=
/p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: =
0 0 20px 0;">So they focused in on a specific idea: what if we could get cu=
stomers to generate content themselves, structure the data they generate, a=
nd then charge everyone a subscription fee to access the growing treasure t=
rove of information?&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">With that reframing, the pushback g=
ot more specific. Some investors, believing that the information they glean=
ed from the questions they asked was proprietary, didn&#8217;t feel comfort=
able sharing transcripts of their calls on the platform. Then one investor =
said, &#8220;I&#8217;d be interested in doing this, but I&#8217;d need a la=
g time.&#8221; Tom and Mike asked him how much lag time he&#8217;d need, an=
d he said two weeks. So they went back to other investors and asked if they=
&#8217;d feel comfortable with a two-week lag time, and many of them said y=
es.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Through this process, they tweaked and iterate=
d the details until it formed a clear outline of the product. Then, they we=
nt back and met with </span><em>more</em><span> customers. The goal was to =
discover an &#8220;</span><strong>Over My Dead Body Product</strong><span>&=
#8221;: a product so useful to customers that if someone threatened to take=
 it away, that&#8217;s how they&#8217;d respond.&#160;</span></p><p style=
=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
">Then one day, on one of those exploratory calls, they found something clo=
se. An investor told the Elnicks, &#8220;Send us something to sign. We&#821=
7;ll pay you when you launch, and we&#8217;ll start doing calls now to buil=
d up the library.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That was huge. Getting people t=
o nod along in agreement is one thing. Getting them to loop in their ops an=
d legal teams to hash out and sign a contract, before a single line of code=
 had been written, was another.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Without building a=
 product, Tegus had started to find product-market fit. That defined an app=
roach the company uses to this day: </span><strong>Sell-Design-Build</stron=
g><span>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Over the next six weeks, 40 customers=
 signed up.</strong><span>&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">So what were they sign=
ing up for? What model emerged from those hundreds of conversations?&#160;<=
/p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: =
0 0 20px 0;"><span>As one investor they spoke to told them, &#8220;Go study=
 Costco, because this is the </span><strong>Costco model</strong><span>.&#8=
221;&#160;</span></p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget" style=3D"-moz-=
osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; color=
: #404040; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystem=
Font, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji'=
, 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bol=
d; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;"><stro=
ng>The Tegus Business Model</strong></h3><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The unlock was sim=
ple in retrospect: instead of charging investors a markup on every expert c=
all and keeping them siloed, like an expensive matchmaking service, </span>=
<strong>Tegus charges investors a subscription fee to access the platform, =
and then lets them book expert calls at cost.&#160;</strong></p><p style=3D=
"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">O=
n the surface, it&#8217;s the Costco model: sell the product at breakeven, =
make money on the membership.&#160;</p><div class=3D"captioned-image-contai=
